1. Definitions
Commercial entity: a for profit corporation or sole proprietorship bringing in over $10,000 in sales a year for over 90 days, with sales $ numbers calclated by any accurate method of your choice. 

source: for software, source means the uncompiled code, for electronics, source means editable schematic files exported by a eda or CAD program. for others, it is all the files used to make a finished product

noncomercial entity: any US or EU member country nonprofit or anyone or corporation who isn't classified as a commercial entity.

2. Redistributability
Projects licensed under the Marican Community License have limited distributability. If you are a non-commercial entity, projects have free derivative redistributability as long as they are also shared under the Marican Community License. If you are a commercial entity, your rights are limited heavily. For internal use, you are considered a non-commercial entity. for use in commercial products, A "handshake" model is applied. derivitive works are not allowed in the traditional way, eg. a modified version of someone elses circuit boards. what is allowed is using this as a reference freely to create your own designs or modification kits for someone elses projects, eg a HAT for someone elses circuit board(these don't have to be redistributed under the marican community license).

3. License intercompatibility
This license is not currently inter compatible with sny other outside licenses, although it is forward compatible with new releases of this license in the 1.X level , but not releases with a diffrent first didget like 2.X. if you want to make a intercompatible license, please contact me (Marican Engineering) through github issues and inter compatibility may be merged in to a future release.

4. Exceptions to limited distribution rights
Certain companies (eg pine64) that are considered for profit legally but have low profit margins and contribute to the open source community. our way of measuring this is through a bracketed system, if that company qualifies, they have to distribute their derivitive changes, similar to gnu, but can otherwise act as a non commercial, here are the brackets in max annual net income to profit margin:

10K-50K: 35%
50K-100K: 32%
100K-500K: 28%
500K-1M: 20%
1M+: 18%

5. Acceptable timeline: when you need to release your derivative work under this license, there is an acceptable timeline for how long you can take to release it. For software, non commercial entities have 45 days after compiled binaries are distributed to distribute the uncompiled source code via GitHub, gitlab, your own website, or any other other freely available platform. For software for commercial use distributed traditionally through online download or via physical software release, you have 14 days from the day first available via the original release form to release uncompiled source code. Having API keys or secret keys not distributed is acceptable as long as a generic files with comments explaining where API keys or secrets go. For software distributed internally in a product(eg. firmware for a 3d printer), you have the longer of the two, if sent to beta testers or reviewers with a embargo, 45 days after the embargo fully ends, unless embargo fully ends after commercial availability, In which case, this option is void. the other option is 30 days after general corporate availability. For hardware, you have 30 days if you are a commercial entity and 45 days if you are not a commercial entity

6. Responsibility of licensor
Anything licensed under the Marican Community License has NO WARRANTY OR GUARANTEES ATTACHED unless expressly specified by the licensor.

7. Changes to license terms
When you distribute something under the Marican Community License, you agree that you are distributing under the acknowledgement that if someone downloads something under the Marican Community License, you can not change the license terms on people who have already downloaded that from you on that file they have already downloaded, although you can roll out an updated version under a new license. the exception is that if you switch income brackets and no longer are considered noncomercial, you may only make reliability changes, but may continue distributing the current version, although you may no longer make major changes while being grandfathered in to the noncomercial level. 



